	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>OECD highlights opportunities for fundamental CAP reform</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Recent analysis published by OECD highlights how with high commodity prices European farmers are now ‘much less dependent on income support’, offering EU governments ‘a unique opportunity’ to fundamentally reform the CAP. According to Ken Ash, OECD Director of Trade and Agriculture, ‘a window has opened for re-orientation of policy away from broad income support and towards investments in a strong and competitive agri-food sector.’ The OECD analysis points out that EU farmers ‘earned 22% of total annual receipts from government support over the 2008-10 period, down from 39% annually over the 1986-88 period’. Despite this development, CAP expenditures continue to account for 45% of the total EU budget at around €53 billion per annum.</p><p>Recommendations for the future that are advanced in the OECD report include:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘the removal of remaining impediments to the functioning of input and output markets’;</li>

<li>more open access to the European market for land, production quotas and payment entitlements;</li>

<li>‘greater investment in agricultural innovation’;</li>

<li>the establishment of a new EU-wide ‘framework for risk management’;</li>

<li>‘targeted efforts to improve the environmental performance of agriculture, including direct payments to farmers, when necessary, for provision of environmental goods and services’.</li>

</ul>
<p>The OECD analysis implicitly goes beyond current EC proposals to cap direct aid payments, and warns that the current approach could ‘encourage the break-up of larger farms’, thereby losing some of the current economies of scale enjoyed in some EU member states. The OECD report argues that ‘more could be achieved with less if only those who needed support were targeted’.</p><p>The OECD analysis further notes, in the context of EC proposals for ‘greening the CAP’, that ‘early attempts to attach environmental conditions to direct payments have been shown to have had a limited impact on the environmental performance of agriculture’. Concern was also expressed at the implicit set-aside aspects of some of the ‘greening’ proposals in a context of rapidly expanding demand and a slowdown in yield growth.</p><p>Copa-Cogeca, the European farmers’ organisation, has recently called for a CAP reform that focuses on ‘reinforcing the production role of farmers’. Copa President Gerd Sonnleitner argues that some of the ‘greening’ proposals tabled by the EC would impose further costs on farmers, and that the EC must therefore focus on ‘economically viable’ green growth measures.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>OECD, ‘Europe has unique opportunity to reform farm support, says OECD’, 5 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.oecd.org/document/21/0,3746,en_21571361_44315115_48813909_1_1_1_1,00.html" target="_self">http://www.oecd.org/document/21/0,3746,en_21571361_44315115_48813909_1_1...</a></p><p><i>EurActiv.com</i>, ‘OECD urges EU to reform farm support’, 6 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.euractiv.com/cap/oecd-urges-eu-reform-farm-support-news-508160" target="_self">http://www.euractiv.com/cap/oecd-urges-eu-reform-farm-support-news-508160</a></p><p>Copa-Cogeca, ‘Copa-Cogeca presidents unveil views on future CAP at major seminar’, 6 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive&amp;lang=en" target="_self">http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive&amp;lang=en</a></p><p>OECD, ‘Evaluation of agricultural policy reforms in the European Union’, summary, undated</p><p>
<a href="http://www.oecd.org/document/23/0,3746,en_2649_37401_48761687_1_1_1_37401,00.html#access" target="_self">http://www.oecd.org/document/23/0,3746,en_2649_37401_48761687_1_1_1_3740...</a></p><p>OECD, ‘Evaluation of agricultural policy reforms in the European Union’, point of access to all chapters of the OECD report urging the EU to reform farm support,</p><p>
<a href="http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/agriculture-and-food/evaluation-of-agricultural-policy-reforms-in-the-european-union_9789264112124-en" target="_self">http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/agriculture-and-food/evaluation-of-agricult...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Global agricultural price volatility is leading to considerable policy emphasis being placed on ensuring effective ‘safety nets’ for EU producers are maintained. The system of direct aid payments is seen in many EU member states as being central to the attainment of this objective. In this context while the EC is likely to be open to the development and promotion of new risk management instruments to manage price volatility in line with the recent G20 proposals (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/General/G20-agriculture-ministers-agreed-on-action-plan-on-high-food-prices" target="_blank">G20 ministers agree action plan on high food prices</a>’, August 2011) and is looking to further develop its policy on strengthening the functioning of agricultural supply chains, it is looking to retain in place the traditional system of direct aid payments until the effectiveness of alternative methods of managing price volatility has been proven.</p><p>This EU approach of retaining in place a range of traditional policy tools (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Agricultural-dimensions-of-the-WTO-EU-trade-policy-review" target="_blank">Agricultural dimensions of the WTO EU trade policy review</a>’, August 2011), while alternative policy measures are set in place to deal with evolving global trade challenges in the food and agricultural sector, potentially holds important lessons for ACP governments, as they too seek to manage strategically important national agricultural markets in the context of heightened price volatility within a trend towards rising global agricultural prices.</p>
		</div>
		
